2i\u221a1\u2212gei\u03b1\n\n\u221age\u2212i\u03c6\n\n\u0013\n\n[such that \u0303S=1 for u=0]\n\n(39.19)\n\nwith \u03b1 = \u03c6 = 0 and\n\ng\n\n= t 2\n\n=\n\n1\n\n1 + (u/vE)2\n\n=\n\n(cos(\u03b3))2\n\n(39.20)\n\nThe advantage of the ad-hoc convention is the possibility to regard u = 0 as the unperturbed Hamiltonian, and to\n\nuse the T matrix formalism to find the \u0303S matrix.", "embedding": [-0.017600453, 0.02145957, 0.027377315, 0.012501019, -0.05087249, -0.021575542, -0.005208426, -0.010476657, -0.055341106, 0.09307071, 0.036526617, 0.00928074, -0.012465144, -0.021546546, -0.0345746, 0.025146527, -0.013176926, -0.018557258, -0.10179126, 0.030022478, 0.022462113, -0.0068027717, -0.063432656, -0.028556185, -0.03855764, 0.03380818, 0.0130034415, 0.005724642, 0.048554927, 0.028653074, -0.001239203, -0.029164143, 0.02414632, -0.05110074, 0.004735409, -0.02180718, -0.004942299, -0.04878658, -0.0018253137, -0.026206268, 0.05372428, 0.004495211, -0.006287919, -0.026801651, 0.005940492, -0.04228821, -0.013838889, -0.00862831, -0.05478301, -0.067485586, -0.04069624, -0.002391079, 0.027225314, -0.020402962, -0.004299576, 0.0052330336, -0.017622307, 0.012091235, -0.0134735685, 0.01614749, 0.029396184, -0.002337248, 0.0021002663, -0.027574278, -0.0008636953, 0.017415145, -0.007599644, 0.052021775, 0.025388414, -0.01925649, 0.0032569796, -0.004601437, -0.008027921, -0.018139057, -0.024179831, 0.041636135, 0.032020472, -0.011115628, -0.041453436, 0.007187718, 0.011173909, -0.0059265667, -0.03140494, 0.0049229376, -0.021612665, 0.010471417, 0.0012932188, -0.00528293, 0.02143738, 0.00235404, 0.04734807, 0.066412225, 0.024407081, 0.01630392, 0.035601374, -0.003629451, 0.007846693, 0.020495329, 0.01014112, 0.011843919, 0.00077729946, 0.06581472, -0.013263729, 0.036019035, -0.030879216, 0.029365072, -0.008630038, 0.052829254, -0.012374481, -0.030692285, 0.014360838, -0.015223598, -0.004657763, 0.021071192, -0.0035756554, 0.032885667, 0.010403734, 0.024040751, -0.01189144, -0.0318